1
00:00:00,740 --> 00:00:09,771
Namo Dasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa

2
00:00:10,307 --> 00:00:34,171
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:42,033 --> 00:00:50,043
This morning we discussed or talked about these three characteristics.

4
00:00:51,045 --> 00:00:59,637
And what we were concerned with is the first of the Noble Eightfold Path, this business of right view, right understanding.

5
00:01:03,643 --> 00:01:10,572
And what the Buddha is saying is that it's actually in the way that we're looking which is at fault.

6
00:01:12,204 --> 00:01:15,968
It's the way we understand things.

7
00:01:15,989 --> 00:01:29,786
And the quality of that understanding is deep within the actual intelligence that we are.

8
00:01:30,947 --> 00:01:34,370
The Buddha, for want of a better word, the Buddha nature within.

9
00:01:34,411 --> 00:01:38,756
And we call it a delusion.

10
00:01:38,775 --> 00:01:40,237
He calls it a delusion.

11
00:01:41,888 --> 00:02:07,490
and the definition of a delusion is that of course you don't know you're deluded this is the problem if somebody is deluded what we're saying is that they don't know how mad they are so here we are you see completely mad and not knowing it and something awakens us to that delusion

12
00:02:08,128 --> 00:02:35,098
and it's suffering the Buddha actually says quite clearly that it's suffering that coming to look at suffering which leads us to the end of suffering so although it's not a pleasant thing it actually is a goal for us to find where the end of suffering is how we can bring suffering to an end I like to tell my sad tale with an optician on this occasion

13
00:02:36,479 --> 00:02:43,645
I got these new pair of glasses and the left eye felt uncomfortable.

14
00:02:43,665 --> 00:02:46,808
But as far as I could see, I saw properly.

15
00:02:48,430 --> 00:02:52,533
So I went back and I said, the left eye feels uncomfortable.

16
00:02:52,554 --> 00:02:55,456
And she tested me, there's another optician.

17
00:02:55,477 --> 00:02:56,798
I said it was a wrong prescription.

18
00:02:57,618 --> 00:03:01,443
It had not taken into account astigmatism.

19
00:03:01,462 --> 00:03:05,727
Now for those of you with 20-20 eyesight, astigmatism...

20
00:03:06,061 --> 00:03:08,104
is a sort of wave in the lens.

21
00:03:08,525 --> 00:03:13,031
You know, like the old glass used to have a wave and when you look through it, it would distort the image.

22
00:03:13,792 --> 00:03:17,298
So that's what this stigmatism does, you see.

23
00:03:17,318 --> 00:03:21,663
And she corrected it, I had a new lens, and the discomfort disappeared.

24
00:03:23,967 --> 00:03:35,223
Now, what was amazing to me was that I could see no difference between the seeing with the wrong lens and the actual process of seeing with the right lens.

25
00:03:35,322 --> 00:03:39,989
It all seemed exactly the same to me, except that there was a discomfort.

26
00:03:42,473 --> 00:03:47,099
And I think that's a wonderful metaphor for our situation.

27
00:03:47,981 --> 00:03:51,426
That somehow being here is dukkha.

28
00:03:51,526 --> 00:03:53,530
Dukkha means a hard place.

29
00:03:55,973 --> 00:04:02,223
One of the little epithets they use, one of the little descriptions they use, is of an axle which doesn't fit the wheel right.

30
00:04:03,352 --> 00:04:06,918
It's just not quite right.

31
00:04:08,340 --> 00:04:25,305
And that essential sort of delusion, that essential wrong way of looking is what we're trying to correct when we see these three characteristics.

32
00:04:26,228 --> 00:04:29,713
So we're in a better position than the Buddha himself because when he started off,

33
00:04:30,723 --> 00:04:35,468
there would seem to be very little information as to where suffering might arise.

34
00:04:37,891 --> 00:04:46,641
And through his own efforts, he came to be able to pinpoint exactly where the problem lay.

35
00:04:48,903 --> 00:04:56,894
And we talked this morning about a mistake, you see, because the process begins at the level of not knowing.

36
00:04:57,413 --> 00:04:59,716
And it's through not knowing that we presume to know.

37
00:05:02,920 --> 00:05:04,802
So as a child, what do we know?

38
00:05:07,725 --> 00:05:08,245
There you are.

39
00:05:09,567 --> 00:05:10,067
Gurgling.

40
00:05:11,949 --> 00:05:12,350
Weeping.

41
00:05:14,072 --> 00:05:16,634
And you just presume yourself to be this little bundle of flesh.

42
00:05:17,976 --> 00:05:18,858
And it just continues.

43
00:05:20,038 --> 00:05:23,742
And as we said this morning, what we're trying to do is to create heaven on earth.

44
00:05:25,404 --> 00:05:29,230
Interestingly enough, no religion predicts heaven on earth.

45
00:05:29,490 --> 00:05:31,391
They always say you have to die, then you go.

46
00:05:32,047 --> 00:05:33,028
You can't get it here.

47
00:05:33,410 --> 00:05:38,742
You get a glimpse of it here, but you can't maintain it here because of the situation of the world.

48
00:05:42,149 --> 00:05:49,144
So, when we come to see that, our next

49
00:05:50,204 --> 00:06:02,829
Our next task, as it were, having seen the problem, having seen that we create continuity where there isn't continuity, we create solidity, substantiality, a sense of self where there isn't one.

50
00:06:03,704 --> 00:06:06,666
and we try to find happiness in the world which can't deliver.

51
00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:19,822
So once we begin to sort of understand that, begin to see that in ourselves, then the next question comes up is, well, how do we then create the transformation?

52
00:06:19,843 --> 00:06:20,903
How do we then become Buddha?

53
00:06:21,884 --> 00:06:27,872
Because that's what he did, and he said there was no distinction to be made between himself and anybody else.

54
00:06:28,156 --> 00:06:52,281
So our problem is now, having perceived these wrong views, these wrong understanding, is how do we proceed in order to get rid of our suffering and, and this is the positive side remember, to end up with this beautiful mind, the beautiful mind, the beautiful heart.

55
00:06:52,302 --> 00:06:54,805
So remember that once the Buddha had

56
00:06:55,779 --> 00:06:58,004
liberated himself from that delusion.

57
00:06:59,267 --> 00:07:05,341
It wasn't as though he turned into some sort of gormless, amorphic blob sat by the road.

58
00:07:06,745 --> 00:07:08,569
He was obviously quite charismatic.

59
00:07:09,911 --> 00:07:12,978
In fact, very shortly after his death,

60
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:27,305
enlightenment, his awakening, he actually is wandering to see these five earlier companions to tell them about what he has to teach them, and he meets one of these ascetics on the way.

61
00:07:28,230 --> 00:07:33,740
And the ascetic, who's never forget, says to him, you know, you look so bright, you're gleaming.

62
00:07:33,759 --> 00:07:35,281
He says, you know, what's your understanding?

63
00:07:35,341 --> 00:07:36,244
Who's your teacher?

64
00:07:36,964 --> 00:07:43,875
And he goes into this wonderful self-panegyric about how he is the enlightened one, the fully self-enlightened.

65
00:07:43,896 --> 00:07:48,744
And understandably, the ascetic goes, oh, very interesting.

66
00:07:49,124 --> 00:07:51,267
And then wanders off.

67
00:07:51,288 --> 00:07:55,875
And that was one of his first understandings, that it wasn't quite the way to teach ascetics.

68
00:07:58,370 --> 00:08:05,064
When he actually approaches his disciples, they sort of know him as this Siddhartha who'd been struggling like him.

69
00:08:05,105 --> 00:08:09,514
And they think he's gone soft anyway because he'd eaten and stuff.

70
00:08:09,814 --> 00:08:11,298
And they refuse really to acknowledge him.

71
00:08:11,559 --> 00:08:15,146
But as he comes close, they feel there's something quite strange.

72
00:08:15,329 --> 00:08:39,125
quite different about him and almost um unwillingly they prepare a seat for him and start listening to him and he starts to try and convince them and they and they you know they're saying well yeah yeah yeah and then he says to them have you ever heard me speaking like this before have you ever heard me ever say things like this before and they say no and that's when they open up and um

73
00:08:39,932 --> 00:08:46,499
Even by the end of the first talks, one of them has become on the first rung of enlightenment, the rung of awakening.

74
00:08:49,461 --> 00:08:55,548
So the teaching isn't just about trying to see something, it's about this process of transformation.

75
00:08:56,048 --> 00:08:59,451
And there are two processes that we have to go through.

76
00:08:59,951 --> 00:09:04,697
The first one is the more passive one, and the second one is the active one.

77
00:09:05,677 --> 00:09:09,822
Now the passive one is already happening when we practice Vipassana.

78
00:09:11,134 --> 00:09:26,835
just by turning our gaze away from the symptoms of our disease, away from the symptoms of our wrong view, these symptoms begin to disappear.

79
00:09:29,136 --> 00:09:30,339
What are these symptoms?

80
00:09:30,739 --> 00:09:37,648
These symptoms are the five, what he, he split them up into these five hindrances.

81
00:09:37,948 --> 00:09:40,453
So there are all the things that we desire.

82
00:09:41,596 --> 00:09:45,825
Desire meaning this drive to find happiness in a central world.

83
00:09:46,567 --> 00:09:52,219
There are all those things that we're averse to, get angry about, upset about.

84
00:09:52,239 --> 00:09:55,806
There are all those things that we get...

85
00:09:56,308 --> 00:10:22,738
that habit we have of going into oblivion to escape problems, you know, like when you feel a bit off, you feel a bit things got on top of you, or you feel a bit down, you get this, you know, neon lights, head for the bed, throw yourself on the couch, disappear for a while, using sleep as a sort of suppressant, well it is a suppressant, push it away, push it down,

86
00:10:24,557 --> 00:10:33,995
All the stuff that makes us restless, and that includes things like guilt and shame, which are secondary emotions arising out of wrong actions.

87
00:10:35,697 --> 00:10:41,246
And doubts, doubts that doggers, not only spiritual doubts, just ordinary doubts.

88
00:10:41,267 --> 00:10:45,254
Doubts, this is the right job, should I be with this person, should I not be with this person?

89
00:10:45,956 --> 00:10:47,899
Just doubts that doggers, you see.

90
00:10:48,470 --> 00:11:02,006
and doubts that are not, shall we say, honest doubts, for want of a better word, a sort of sense of wonder, but doubts which rest upon fear, fear of commitment.

91
00:11:03,572 --> 00:11:14,850
So all these turbulence that we have, all the depressions, all the anxieties, all the guilt and the shame, all the rubbish that slides inside us, these are all symptoms.

92
00:11:15,191 --> 00:11:17,875
They're all symptoms of this fundamental mistake.

93
00:11:19,317 --> 00:11:22,442
That doesn't mean to say that you can't treat them as symptoms.

94
00:11:22,422 --> 00:11:52,176
often when I speak like this people think that I'm talking against things like you know therapy and stuff like that not at all but therapy itself won't actually get to the root of the problem although it's obviously can be extremely helpful there was a book called you might have some of you might know it emotional intelligence yeah you know that book well there was another

95
00:11:52,577 --> 00:12:00,091
There was another author, a woman, who wrote Intelligent Emotions as a sort of commentary.

96
00:12:00,533 --> 00:12:01,514
And it's an excellent book.

97
00:12:02,135 --> 00:12:08,889
Her understanding of how we make these emotions worse and worse is second to none.

98
00:12:10,792 --> 00:12:12,696
But the preface says...

99
00:12:12,878 --> 00:12:16,046
tells us quite distinctly that there is no end to suffering.

100
00:12:16,888 --> 00:12:19,654
It's a Freudian position where all we can do is accommodate.

101
00:12:20,216 --> 00:12:27,495
We can only come to this position of a sort of sanity about life, where it's always going to be uncomfortable and there's no way out of that.

102
00:12:28,386 --> 00:12:32,913
Which isn't a particularly...

103
00:12:33,254 --> 00:12:37,322
But I mean, as truthful as she, from her point of view, perfectly truthful.

104
00:12:38,003 --> 00:12:41,187
So that we can sort of cut the hard edge of our suffering.

105
00:12:41,227 --> 00:12:44,352
We can sort of cut the sharp edge of it.

106
00:12:44,452 --> 00:12:48,058
But basically, we simply cannot be happy at all.

107
00:12:48,078 --> 00:12:48,899
There's no end to it.

108
00:12:49,500 --> 00:12:50,562
At least in this lifetime.

109
00:12:53,868 --> 00:13:10,677
and the reason is that when you read you see that she hasn't quite perceived where the core problem lies and the core problem lies in not seeing these three characteristics now when we avert our gaze to those three characteristics

110
00:13:11,889 --> 00:13:13,312
The hindrances still come up.

111
00:13:13,854 --> 00:13:14,375
They come up.

112
00:13:14,755 --> 00:13:16,418
We can see them in our fantasies.

113
00:13:17,041 --> 00:13:21,951
We suddenly get caught up on some erotic, lustful or romantic dream.

114
00:13:22,351 --> 00:13:25,378
We're suddenly building a huge business which is going to take the world over.

115
00:13:25,678 --> 00:13:26,841
We're suddenly saving the world.

116
00:13:26,860 --> 00:13:28,144
That's a lovely one.

117
00:13:28,309 --> 00:13:35,625
And we suddenly have the answers to our climate problems, you know, all these lovely compassionate ideas.

118
00:13:36,668 --> 00:13:48,293
So that's all desire, even if it's arising out of, shall we say, some sort of compassion or some sort of love, it's still a production of the ego of wanting to save the world.

119
00:13:51,174 --> 00:13:56,562
You'll notice that the direction is always to stop the dream, to stop the fantasy.

120
00:13:57,162 --> 00:13:58,023
That's your symptom.

121
00:13:58,283 --> 00:14:00,767
The fantasy is the symptom of the disorder.

122
00:14:01,927 --> 00:14:10,678
And then when you come in, at least you're at a secondary level of the disorder, which is the emotional state that you can experience.

123
00:14:10,698 --> 00:14:19,409
So as you descend into the body, and the answer always lies in the body, as you descend into the body and you feel that restlessness,

124
00:14:20,268 --> 00:14:45,398
see then the questions may arise why is this where's it come from etc etc so that's again treating with the symptom the Buddha's image for that is of a man who shot by an arrow so we all know it and they come to help him take the out of out and he said well hold on he says I want to know who fired it why they find it who made the arrow well right well before they know he's dead

125
00:14:47,554 --> 00:14:53,783
So it's a case of recognizing that even here the fundamental answer to our problems doesn't lie.

126
00:14:55,647 --> 00:15:10,508
Asking those questions may be interesting, you know, might be interesting to have a nice therapeutic session with somebody and find out why that happened, but it won't actually pull the original thorn out of the system.

127
00:15:11,482 --> 00:15:13,245
So again we avert our gaze.

128
00:15:13,284 --> 00:15:18,770
We're not concerned with the problem as such, the problem of this restlessness.

129
00:15:20,131 --> 00:15:32,664
We're now concerned with either seeing its transient nature or the fact that we distance from it and we create in that distance a feeling of it being not me, not mine.

130
00:15:34,346 --> 00:15:41,254
When we do that, to our amazement, the thing begins to evaporate, begins to exhaust itself.

131
00:15:41,740 --> 00:15:47,366
And that's one way that we come to understand that these emotions, these states don't have any reality.

132
00:15:47,386 --> 00:15:49,929
They don't have any substance to them at all.

133
00:15:50,250 --> 00:15:51,932
They're just forms of energy.

134
00:15:52,972 --> 00:16:03,985
And in allowing them to dissipate like that, we begin to see that when it comes to this therapy level of things, the wonder of the system is that you don't have to do anything.

135
00:16:04,527 --> 00:16:06,229
You don't have to do a damn thing.

136
00:16:06,830 --> 00:16:09,773
You just have to sit there and bear it.

137
00:16:10,461 --> 00:16:37,735
sit there and allow it to express itself and in so doing it's just a force it just evaporates the other thing that we can do apart from seeing it from these two vantage points of it being impermanent transient getting into the into the texture of the feeling

138
00:16:38,221 --> 00:16:48,490
the actual texture, the different little sensations that arise with that restlessness in the heart or in the body.

139
00:16:48,509 --> 00:16:51,960
And this other business of creating that distance

140
00:16:52,666 --> 00:16:55,190
So that it's quite clear it's not me, not mine.

141
00:16:56,211 --> 00:17:01,081
There's a little warning there that sometimes we're using that to actually gently suppress it.

142
00:17:01,421 --> 00:17:01,922
Be careful.

143
00:17:02,423 --> 00:17:08,854
When you're noting something like restlessness, restlessness, careful you're not using the word to sort of gently kill it.

144
00:17:09,796 --> 00:17:10,676
Because you won't kill it.

145
00:17:11,057 --> 00:17:13,442
All you're doing is just gently pushing it away.

146
00:17:14,249 --> 00:17:21,522
That distancing is a little technique which allows us to regain a certain equanimity within a situation.

147
00:17:21,702 --> 00:17:31,080
But once that equanimity is gained, we have to go into it, we have to feel it, to experience it.

148
00:17:31,101 --> 00:17:36,612
And at that point, it's more impermanent, insubstantial quality of that becomes permanent.

149
00:17:36,945 --> 00:17:44,455
more apparent, and it's seeing its non-substantial nature which undermines the idea of it being a me, a mine.

150
00:17:46,919 --> 00:17:50,944
Now, that's at that... No, wait till the end.

151
00:17:51,465 --> 00:18:05,805
Now, the third approach is by way of a very simple psychology which is open to everybody, and that is having experienced this restlessness

152
00:18:05,869 --> 00:18:21,549
to catch our relationship to it our perhaps aversion to it or our desire to indulge it either way we're actually turning the turbulence we're actually steering the turbulence

153
00:18:22,778 --> 00:18:32,090
When you suppress it, the very force with which you suppress it with, that negative force of pushing it away, simply feeds back into the system.

154
00:18:32,111 --> 00:18:34,976
And it's like a spring that's waiting to be sprung.

155
00:18:35,635 --> 00:18:37,859
And it comes up with the energy of that resistance.

156
00:18:40,022 --> 00:18:45,711
And as you resist it, your attention is on the feeling of that resistance.

157
00:18:46,392 --> 00:18:48,474
Is it just an aversion or is it fear?

158
00:18:49,076 --> 00:18:52,701
Or is it subtly moving from fear to aversion?

159
00:18:53,186 --> 00:18:55,632
Fear and aversion are two sides of the same coin.

160
00:18:55,672 --> 00:18:56,894
They're very close together.

161
00:18:56,933 --> 00:19:02,203
Anger and anxiety, fear and hatred are very close.

162
00:19:03,405 --> 00:19:07,272
And the mind, and you can switch from one to the other almost at lightning speed.

163
00:19:08,976 --> 00:19:15,448
This was apparent to me when I was rather, I confess, cruel to a little pup.

164
00:19:16,711 --> 00:19:21,298
I was playing with it and I kept pushing it away and it kept barking at me.

165
00:19:21,317 --> 00:19:24,041
But when I pushed it too much, it would whine with fear.

166
00:19:24,762 --> 00:19:33,655
And I could see very clearly that my same action of pushing it and pushing it away created a dual movement within this little being.

167
00:19:34,257 --> 00:19:37,381
One minute it was barking at me fiercely and the next minute it was trying to get away.

168
00:19:38,343 --> 00:19:42,769
And that's all we're doing all the time with anything that we feel negative towards.

169
00:19:44,622 --> 00:19:57,332
But of course there is this other more, sorry, the great thing about aversion or fear is at least it distances us from the object, at least we can create a sort of not wanting, not wanting that.

170
00:19:57,615 --> 00:20:01,340
In a sort of paradoxical way, it does make us stick to the object.

171
00:20:01,961 --> 00:20:09,991
You know this, for instance, if you've lived in a place where you've heard next door's music and it's come through just as a sort of continuous thump of the bass.

172
00:20:10,613 --> 00:20:13,757
Dum, da-dum, dum, da-dum, you see?

173
00:20:14,157 --> 00:20:15,519
And this aversion comes.

174
00:20:15,638 --> 00:20:18,202
Well, you just cannot get your ear off that wall.

175
00:20:19,704 --> 00:20:23,249
The aversion makes your ear stick to that wall more and more and more.

176
00:20:24,049 --> 00:20:27,555
And as soon as the aversion goes or you're distracted, you don't hear it anymore.

177
00:20:28,480 --> 00:20:38,709
So the peculiar thing about aversion and fear is that it attaches you to the object while at the same time distancing it.

178
00:20:38,729 --> 00:20:41,632
But it still has to be observed, it still has to be felt.

179
00:20:42,092 --> 00:20:44,193
And again, this is a conditioning.

180
00:20:44,934 --> 00:20:56,444
So if you try to suppress that, if you try to push that away, you find yourself in the same old situation where you're empowering the negativity within yourself.

181
00:20:58,416 --> 00:21:00,441
So again, it's a case of opening up.

182
00:21:00,981 --> 00:21:08,438
See, that's this business of that default position where you allow things to come in their fullness.

183
00:21:09,641 --> 00:21:13,167
And you're aware of that fear, of that aversion that might come.

184
00:21:15,005 --> 00:21:19,250
As it comes up sometimes, it comes up at a speed which is difficult to handle.

185
00:21:19,349 --> 00:21:27,538
Sometimes, as it were, our openness allows it to manifest too quickly for us, and you find yourself perhaps feeling a bit panicky.

186
00:21:28,398 --> 00:21:31,162
So when that happens, you just chill out.

187
00:21:32,103 --> 00:21:36,428
You just sort of cool the whole system and regain your equanimity.

188
00:21:37,509 --> 00:21:41,973
And the way to do that, if it's very bad, is just to get up in the posture and just go for a walk.

189
00:21:42,307 --> 00:21:59,067
But if it's not that bad, just to put your attention on a neutral sensation, like your breath or your knees or your hands, you see, and that neutrality allows you to, allows that reaction, shall we say, to begin to diminish.

190
00:22:03,487 --> 00:22:08,738
At a much more subtle level, there is that identity, that indulgence.

191
00:22:09,378 --> 00:22:18,238
And that, of course, is extremely difficult to counteract because it's such a conditioned force in us to indulge what we like.

192
00:22:18,859 --> 00:22:24,788
But even so, when that feeling comes, something that's desirable, you see, you have to be with it.

193
00:22:25,367 --> 00:22:36,403
Now let's take, for instance, some dream that we have, something that we want to achieve in our lives, and the mind is constantly creating scenarios whereby we can achieve it.

194
00:22:37,523 --> 00:22:40,327
Let's say, set up a small business or something.

195
00:22:40,425 --> 00:22:48,138
So you see here in meditation we're observing how this desire is constantly manufacturing this inner world.

196
00:22:49,280 --> 00:22:54,130
And remember that everything that human beings have done have started with that image.

197
00:22:54,871 --> 00:23:02,203
Everything that you see from jet planes to computers to whatever you see has always begun with an idea.

198
00:23:02,744 --> 00:23:05,269
It's always begun coming out of the mind.

199
00:23:06,025 --> 00:23:30,717
As you come off that desire and you come back into the body and you may feel that sort of excitement that's around it, keep your attention within the body, but if you can, just feel that energy which is moving out to create the world, which is moving out to create the dream.

200
00:23:31,574 --> 00:23:34,676
you can feel it, it's quite a strong pull.

201
00:23:35,397 --> 00:24:00,061
Now, if your attention stays with the original excitement in the body, and with that feeling of wanting to go back into the dream world, if you stay at that level of feeling, and you wait until this power, which wants to manifest the excitement as a dream, and you wait for it to die away, you see, then you'll see, you're emptying the mind of that desire.

202
00:24:02,184 --> 00:24:06,672
And that's not that difficult to do so long as you know where to look for it, see?

203
00:24:07,192 --> 00:24:11,220
And the way you look for it is always starting with that physical base.

204
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:13,923
You can't do it in the mind, the mind's too quick.

205
00:24:14,846 --> 00:24:20,193
Once you've manifested through a mind, through a dream, you've lost it, you've become unconscious, you might say.

206
00:24:20,815 --> 00:24:24,260
You've lost that sort of awareness, that mindfulness.

207
00:24:24,832 --> 00:24:37,743
So that's why when you wake up from a dream, you see, you note, planning, planning, that gives you the in, you know what, something is in the heart that wants to achieve something.

208
00:24:37,763 --> 00:24:42,468
And that's when you come back down into the body and try to contact it.

209
00:24:42,488 --> 00:24:45,871
If you can't contact it, fine, you just stay with the breath, it's not a problem.

210
00:24:47,732 --> 00:24:53,758
So anything to do with desire, which is the first of these hindrances,

211
00:24:54,008 --> 00:24:58,614
you know, try to find that excitement in the body, whatever it might be.

212
00:24:59,736 --> 00:25:02,900
And then that movement that wants to manifest it.

213
00:25:02,920 --> 00:25:04,061
And just stay there.

214
00:25:04,402 --> 00:25:07,626
And again, remind yourself, you don't have to do anything.

215
00:25:09,128 --> 00:25:10,631
You don't have to do a single thing.

216
00:25:10,651 --> 00:25:14,355
All you have to do is allow the energy to manifest.

217
00:25:14,375 --> 00:25:17,559
And this is our, we say, unfortunate position.

218
00:25:18,560 --> 00:25:23,407
These turbulences, these turbulences

219
00:25:25,025 --> 00:25:30,092
cannot release themselves except into consciousness.

220
00:25:30,112 --> 00:25:44,029
And they've only got two ways to go, either through some feeling emotional state, or if they're too suppressed, too repressed, they'll come out through the body as illness, or at least as some form of discomfort.

221
00:25:44,049 --> 00:25:50,137
So that's why in your meditation you get, you know, people get headaches, they feel nausea, they get backaches.

222
00:25:50,708 --> 00:25:55,093
And all that is this turbulence manifesting through the body.

223
00:25:56,413 --> 00:26:03,021
And once they go, something goes, but you never know what it, for the most part, you never know what the hell it was.

224
00:26:03,041 --> 00:26:04,323
All you know is that something's gone.

225
00:26:06,746 --> 00:26:17,498
Even, say, for about four to five weeks, I was just getting this continual pain at the back of my neck for seemingly no reason.

226
00:26:17,538 --> 00:26:18,858
I couldn't understand it at all.

227
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:45,301
and then it just disappeared and it's just one of those things so as your psyche begins to empty itself as your psychology begins to purify itself this process of purification is always a process which is not particularly pleasant and you have to be prepared for that

228
00:26:46,345 --> 00:26:53,291
So it's the same with these other things such as all the hatreds and aversions, the angers that we've got locked in the system.

229
00:26:55,013 --> 00:27:04,022
Once you allow them to manifest as dreams, as fantasies unwittingly, you're developing them.

230
00:27:04,243 --> 00:27:12,251
You know that from your just ordinary daily life experience where somebody has said something to you in the morning which has been just a little upsetting.

231
00:27:12,636 --> 00:27:14,179
And you've brushed it aside, you see.

232
00:27:14,759 --> 00:27:18,244
And then while you're having your cup of tea, you're, bloody, you're coming here.

233
00:27:18,305 --> 00:27:23,933
And by lunchtime, you're biting the fork.

234
00:27:26,297 --> 00:27:27,519
Evening, you're taking aspirin.

235
00:27:30,522 --> 00:27:31,424
And it all builds up.

236
00:27:31,545 --> 00:27:36,893
I mean, the person only insulted you or said something slightly hurtful once.

237
00:27:37,713 --> 00:27:42,441
You've had them repeat it millions of times just to drive the point home

238
00:27:47,855 --> 00:27:59,332
So the danger, so this mind that we have, which is so creative and has created so many beautiful things, the music, the art and all that, is also incredibly destructive.

239
00:27:59,352 --> 00:28:02,015
And we have to see that within ourselves.

240
00:28:02,375 --> 00:28:15,835
And we have to see, we have to be very clear that when the mind is wandering off on an aversion or whatever it is, that it's not suppressing anything to pull the mind out, to pull the attention out of it.

241
00:28:15,855 --> 00:28:16,916
That's not suppressing it.

242
00:28:17,992 --> 00:28:23,940
And it's of little value to investigate the causes of it.

243
00:28:24,941 --> 00:28:32,971
If it's an obvious thing, like somebody's upsetting you, say at work, who's, say, bullying you, then obviously one has to investigate that.

244
00:28:32,990 --> 00:28:44,523
But in terms of our inner psychology, something that perhaps has been there from childhood and in Buddhist understanding even before, there's absolutely no, there's nothing to be gained by it.

245
00:28:46,259 --> 00:28:49,483
And therefore the attention is now drawn back into the body.

246
00:28:49,884 --> 00:29:03,508
And in a sense it's only through your own practice that you become confident that it's staying with the heart, staying with these turbulences at a feeling level, that they're actually beginning to exhaust themselves.

247
00:29:07,875 --> 00:29:14,786
I wouldn't want to give anybody the wrong impression that, you know, if one works hard enough within a couple of months, one is perfectly...

248
00:29:14,806 --> 00:29:21,394
Think in terms of a quarter century, then to see tremendous progress.

249
00:29:22,757 --> 00:29:31,690
But I think even in the short term, six months or a year, one can see that at least things might be getting just a wee bit better.

250
00:29:34,656 --> 00:29:37,859
Now it's the same with this sloth and torpor.

251
00:29:37,960 --> 00:29:43,486
It's been translated as sloth, which gives it a sort of moral twist.

252
00:29:43,526 --> 00:29:48,832
But this sort of dullness, dullness in the head and a lethargy in the body.

253
00:29:49,373 --> 00:29:57,701
So remember that that's also a consequence of developing that attitude, that of seeking comfort in oblivion.

254
00:29:59,083 --> 00:30:03,027
Not just conking out.

255
00:30:04,795 --> 00:30:08,904
And the great thing about oblivion is that there really is no suffering there.

256
00:30:08,924 --> 00:30:09,526
It's perfect.

257
00:30:10,749 --> 00:30:13,394
There is a place where you can go where there is no suffering.

258
00:30:13,414 --> 00:30:15,800
Unfortunately, we wake up.

259
00:30:18,193 --> 00:30:22,218
And, you know, in the Buddha's understanding, there will always be a waking up.

260
00:30:22,698 --> 00:30:26,141
So long as there's a self, there will be a form of existence.

261
00:30:26,161 --> 00:30:30,325
There will always be a seeking of that consciousness to find expression.

262
00:30:31,065 --> 00:30:37,570
So, recognizing that, you know, be careful in your daily life not to enter into that state.

263
00:30:37,651 --> 00:30:47,559
Rather go for a walk or do something or just keep awake, as it were, not to begin to develop that lethargy.

264
00:30:48,755 --> 00:30:52,405
I mean, you know, in bad cases of depression, I remember a woman.

265
00:30:54,311 --> 00:30:57,561
She was sleeping then 16, 18 hours a day, you see.

266
00:30:59,145 --> 00:31:01,313
Making things sort of worse for herself, really.

267
00:31:05,730 --> 00:31:13,759
Then there's all this business of restlessness, and that can be the cause, that can be caused by anything really, just a sense of restlessness.

268
00:31:14,759 --> 00:31:32,076
And it's a case of, remember, when, just like dullness, when it's in the mind, when there's restlessness in the mind or dullness in the head, you see, to actually put your attention there, just stay with it, attend to it, as a nurse might to a patient.

269
00:31:33,202 --> 00:31:35,146
You don't have to do anything, you just bear with it.

270
00:31:35,708 --> 00:31:41,260
Now when the mind's rushing off all over the place, it's just patiently bringing it back, patiently bringing it back.

271
00:31:43,766 --> 00:31:51,903
Now when we do this business of reflection at the end of a sitting and I say, you know, just reflect on your meditation.

272
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:59,874
If the whole of your meditation you've just been coming back off this turbulent mind, that's a good meditation.

273
00:32:00,474 --> 00:32:05,181
But if you give in, if you say, well, I will think about that, then that's it.

274
00:32:05,260 --> 00:32:10,366
You could say to yourself, that was a really bad meditation.

275
00:32:10,666 --> 00:32:20,759
If you feel that dullness in the head and you're feeling lethargic and you're constantly waking yourself up and stretching the body and opening your eyes and standing up, is it?

276
00:32:21,262 --> 00:32:37,343
And even if it stays with you in your walking meditation, but you're constantly sort of just keeping awake, just keeping above it, making those feelings, those sensations, something to observe, something to feel, experience, then that's a good meditation.

277
00:32:37,363 --> 00:32:49,498
But if at any time you say to yourself, well, I'll just have a kip, knowing full well, knowing full well that there is not real tiredness, then one can say to oneself, that was a bad meditation.

278
00:32:52,718 --> 00:32:53,919
One should feel guilty.

279
00:32:54,779 --> 00:32:55,681
One should feel shame.

280
00:32:56,682 --> 00:33:07,295
So that whenever that thought arises, the shame and the guilt arises with it, which one does not want to suffer.

281
00:33:07,315 --> 00:33:16,465
And the Buddha puts on the same hindrance, this quality of guilt, shame, remorse.

282
00:33:16,726 --> 00:33:22,573
Remorse, of course, is a healing feeling, but it's still not a pleasant feeling, remorse.

283
00:33:24,561 --> 00:33:36,180
So remember that guilt and shame are guilt or, I mean here we talk about the dread of consequences, the dread of consequences.

284
00:33:36,721 --> 00:33:42,609
So it's actually beginning to understand that there's a way in which we are creating our own suffering.

285
00:33:44,132 --> 00:33:52,424
And the true statement would be that we only, we can only create our own suffering and only we create our own suffering.

286
00:33:53,468 --> 00:33:55,290
Nobody can create suffering for us.

287
00:33:55,431 --> 00:34:03,204
It's always the way that we relate to what we're actually experiencing.

288
00:34:03,224 --> 00:34:14,282
So when we perceive that, then we need to take full responsibility for our situation.

289
00:34:15,686 --> 00:34:19,391
Which at first is disappointing, because it's always nice to blame somebody else.

290
00:34:20,266 --> 00:34:23,581
or blame the system or the government.

291
00:34:23,601 --> 00:34:28,081
But actually, when you turn into yourself and you realize that

292
00:34:28,331 --> 00:34:30,255
You're the only one creating your suffering.

293
00:34:30,534 --> 00:34:32,757
I'm the only one creating my suffering.

294
00:34:33,518 --> 00:34:42,530
Taking on that responsibility at least now narrows the avenue of escape to at least just me.

295
00:34:43,311 --> 00:34:45,034
Before I had to change the world.

296
00:34:45,474 --> 00:34:50,442
Before I had to get rid of my enemies and all the people who were making it awful for me.

297
00:34:51,146 --> 00:34:52,570
But now, it's just me.

298
00:34:53,273 --> 00:34:54,376
That makes it very simple.

299
00:34:54,936 --> 00:35:01,173
Because all I have to do now is investigate myself, my own psychology, to realize where I'm making the mistakes.

300
00:35:05,490 --> 00:35:07,976
And the final one is this business of doubt.

301
00:35:08,836 --> 00:35:18,775
So, doubt in the spiritual life is a real, it's a pernicious illness because it stops you committing yourself.

302
00:35:18,916 --> 00:35:22,842
If you doubt the practice, then you won't do it.

303
00:35:22,882 --> 00:35:28,713
If you doubt yourself, if you say that, well, everybody else can do it but not me, then that'll stop you doing it.

304
00:35:28,693 --> 00:35:34,903
So doubt is, this sort of skeptical doubt is something that has to be investigated.

305
00:35:34,923 --> 00:35:36,186
And again, it's very simple.

306
00:35:36,867 --> 00:35:38,708
You don't get caught up in the mind.

307
00:35:38,889 --> 00:35:41,132
You don't get caught up in what the mind is saying.

308
00:35:41,893 --> 00:35:46,922
You go into the feelings of doubt, the feelings that surround this so-called doubt.

309
00:35:46,969 --> 00:36:05,016
And I think invariably you'll find some form of resistance, some form of fear, some form of fear of consequences or lack of confidence, which is only another form of self-aversion, lack of confidence.

310
00:36:05,036 --> 00:36:15,373
And it's investigating it at that level of feeling, at that level of emotional feeling that these things begin to evaporate.

311
00:36:19,014 --> 00:36:23,242
That sense of doubt, don't confuse that with a sense of wonder.

312
00:36:23,842 --> 00:36:26,086
Wonder is the philosopher's emotion, isn't it?

313
00:36:26,106 --> 00:36:28,351
It's the philosopher within us that wonders.

314
00:36:29,032 --> 00:36:33,358
Now that's the emotion, that's the drive that the Buddha actually wants us to develop.

315
00:36:33,900 --> 00:36:35,603
That's what we mean by curiosity.

316
00:36:35,864 --> 00:36:39,690
That's one of the seven factors of enlightenment, the desire of wanting to know.

317
00:36:42,539 --> 00:36:47,103
And it's as though we come from that position of belief, you know, the Buddha said this, therefore it must be right.

318
00:36:47,744 --> 00:36:49,887
It's the Buddha said this, now let's see if it's right for me.

319
00:36:50,226 --> 00:36:53,271
That's our attitude, that's the attitude that he would want us to develop.

320
00:36:54,070 --> 00:36:59,257
So that we go into the investigation always from that position of not sure, don't know.

321
00:37:06,344 --> 00:37:11,230
So now, in your meditation, when you're sitting,

322
00:37:11,344 --> 00:37:17,793
That's part of your process of developing the skills of meditation.

323
00:37:18,695 --> 00:37:26,507
Whenever a mental state arises, you see, if you're not sure as to what to do, make sure you find out.

324
00:37:27,367 --> 00:37:31,313
When a mental state arises, there should arise with it how to deal with it.

325
00:37:34,297 --> 00:37:40,726
And it's through dealing with it in a proper way that this process of purifying the heart is taking place.

326
00:37:42,782 --> 00:38:09,802
so that's why that reflection at the end of a sitting is important even if it's only a single reflection even if it's only just looking back and thinking well now how did I you know how did I fall asleep again you know why did I move at that point you know it's like going back and just saying well okay next time I'll do this next time I'll do that see

327
00:38:10,407 --> 00:38:13,532
Even if you don't do it, even if you forget, that's fine.

328
00:38:13,873 --> 00:38:22,547
Just in your next sitting, when you make the same mistake, note that this has happened before, and that you must make a firm determination not to fall into that same error.

329
00:38:23,208 --> 00:38:35,266
And then very slowly, you just train yourself, just train yourself into the skills of meditation.

330
00:38:35,286 --> 00:38:36,869
So,

331
00:38:39,161 --> 00:39:01,068
here we have, we've got a technique, right, we've all got a technique, a basic way of doing it, watching the breath, noting, going slow, I haven't stressed the going slow, I'll do that tomorrow, and we've got that technique, but we also know what it is we're looking at, so we're looking at

332
00:39:01,436 --> 00:39:10,458
the impermanence, we're looking at the sense of non-substantiality, the not-me, not-mine, the distance that is between the knower and the knowing.

333
00:39:10,478 --> 00:39:16,172
We're looking at the way we react to things, learnt reactions.

334
00:39:17,586 --> 00:39:21,873
And in that, we're looking at all those negative things that come up.

335
00:39:22,614 --> 00:39:30,286
Negative things to do with those things that we desire that cause excitement, that cause us to dream of a better life and all that.

336
00:39:30,766 --> 00:39:32,389
We're looking at all the aversions.

337
00:39:32,610 --> 00:39:35,614
We're looking at this dullness and lethargy.

338
00:39:36,576 --> 00:39:39,740
We're looking at the restlessness and we're looking at the doubt.

339
00:39:40,242 --> 00:39:45,449
But also, we're looking at our responses to those things and not getting caught up

340
00:39:45,429 --> 00:39:47,594
in the indulgence, in the aversion.

341
00:39:50,739 --> 00:39:55,206
So we're constantly lifting ourselves out of the mind with its machinations.

342
00:39:56,427 --> 00:39:59,532
And we're not getting drawn into any history.

343
00:40:00,213 --> 00:40:00,454
You see?

344
00:40:03,079 --> 00:40:07,947
Whatever happened in the past, this is a product which is happening now.

345
00:40:07,967 --> 00:40:12,213
The product itself is the problem, not the past.

346
00:40:15,400 --> 00:40:19,231
It manifests now as this mental state.

347
00:40:20,235 --> 00:40:27,317
In dealing with this mental state, the past loses its effect.

348
00:40:34,047 --> 00:40:38,452
So, when we practice Vipassana, these two things are happening.

349
00:40:39,094 --> 00:40:57,177
We're correcting that initial delusion, that stigmatism in our faculty of knowing, in our intuitive intelligence, in the Buddha within, and we're allowing the heart to purify itself.

350
00:40:57,297 --> 00:41:00,121
That's what Vipassana is doing.

351
00:41:00,141 --> 00:41:03,025
And that's what we're practicing over this weekend.

352
00:41:03,527 --> 00:41:13,559
The positive side, which we practice at the end of the weekend, is how we transform that energy into its opposite.

353
00:41:13,579 --> 00:41:16,362
And that's through the practice of metta.

354
00:41:16,543 --> 00:41:19,806
That's the first step in that transformation.

355
00:41:20,608 --> 00:41:33,163
So in the Eightfold Path, having got the right understanding of how the whole thing works, the psychophysical organism, we then purify the heart, which is part of the attitudinal

356
00:41:33,311 --> 00:41:58,898
the second step and then we begin to work with attitudes to begin to transform them so from hatred to love from cruelty to compassion and so on and then these are established they are confirmed they are developed through right speech right action and right language so that whole process of liberation is systemic

357
00:42:00,059 --> 00:42:06,327
If it stops up in the head, there's a danger of it becoming intellectual and callous.

358
00:42:06,347 --> 00:42:11,856
If it stops in the heart, there's a danger of it becoming mawkish and sentimental.

359
00:42:14,559 --> 00:42:22,771
So that whole process has to be really sort of taken through to its logical conclusion, which is the good life.

360
00:42:25,355 --> 00:42:27,518
The wholesome, virtuous life.

361
00:42:35,699 --> 00:42:39,264
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

362
00:42:39,284 --> 00:42:44,070
May you be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

363
00:42:47,596 --> 00:42:51,001
So, it might be good to do a little walking meditation.

364
00:42:52,782 --> 00:42:53,523
About a quarter of an hour.

365
00:42:53,704 --> 00:42:56,849
Yeah, don't worry about the schedule.

366
00:42:57,210 --> 00:42:59,592
If you do some walking meditation.

367
00:42:59,612 --> 00:43:01,014
Give me about 20 minutes.

368
00:43:02,057 --> 00:43:04,722
And then we'll do another section.

369
00:43:04,742 --> 00:43:05,782
The evening will unfold.

370
00:43:07,545 --> 00:43:09,429
Now, if there's any questions that arise from that.

371
00:43:09,449 --> 00:43:10,429
Oh, we've got a bit of paper.

372
00:43:10,530 --> 00:43:13,293
I should have asked you, I'm sorry.

373
00:43:13,313 --> 00:43:13,735
Yeah.

374
00:43:14,775 --> 00:43:15,637
We'll put a bit of paper.

375
00:43:15,657 --> 00:43:19,782
Where will it be?

376
00:43:19,802 --> 00:43:21,646
Yeah.

377
00:43:21,666 --> 00:43:26,512
If anything arises from that, you know, just put down your questions and all will be revealed.

